04821nam a22005535i 9780822380849DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223808497 a10.1515/97808223808492doi  a(DE-B1597)551938  a(OCoLC)52710881  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.N36bS58 2001eb 7aPOL0070002bisacsh04a791.43/6582221 aSlane, Andrea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Not So Foreign Affair :bFascism, Sexuality, and the Cultural Rhetoric of American Democracy /cAndrea Slane. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b21 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI The Democratic Family -- t1 Nazi Nationalist Melodrama: Science, Myth, and Paternal Authority in Die Goldene Stadt -- t2 American Nationalist Melodrama: Tales of Hitler's Children -- t3 ''Family Values'' and Naziana in Contemporary Right-Wing Media -- tII The Democratic Psyche -- t4 Nazism, Psychology, and the Making of Democratic Subjects -- t5 The American Nazi: Cold War Social Problem Films and National Psychobiography -- t6 Skinheads, Militiamen, and the Legacies of Failed Masculinity -- tIII Democratic Sex -- t7 The Iconology of the Sexy Nazi Woman: Marlene Dietrich as Political Palimpsest -- t8 Sexualized Nazis and Contemporary Popular Political Culture -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn A Not So Foreign Affair Andrea Slane investigates the influence of images of Nazism on debates about sexuality that are central to contemporary American political rhetoric. By analyzing an array of films, journalism, scholarly theories, melodrama, video, and propaganda literature, Slane describes a common rhetoric that emerged during the 1930s and 1940s as a means of distinguishing "democratic sexuality" from that ascribed to Nazi Germany.World War II marked a turning point in the cultural rhetoric of democracy, Slane claims, because it intensified a preoccupation with the political role of private life and pushed sexuality to the center of democratic discourse. Having created tremendous anxiety-and fascination-in American culture, Nazism became associated with promiscuity, sexual perversionand the destruction of the family. Slane reveals how this particular imprint of fascism is used in progressive as well as conservative imagery and language to further their domestic agendas and shows how our cultural engagement with Nazism reflects the inherent tension in democracy between the value of diversity, individual freedoms national identity, and notions of the common good. Finally, she applies her analysis of wartime narratives to contemporary texts, examining anti-abortion, anti-gay, and anti-federal rhetoric, as well as the psychic life of skinheads, censorship debates, and the contemporary fascination with incest.An invaluable resource for understanding the language we use-both visual and narrative-to describe and debate democracy in the United States today, A Not So Foreign Affair will appeal to those interested in cultural studies, film and video studies, American studies, twentieth century history, German studies, rhetoric, and sexuality studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspects. 0aNational socialism and motion pictures. 0aNational socialism in motion pictures. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822380849zCo-access DOI >> c